In their study, Mark England from Exeter, UK, and UC Irvine, USA, and colleagues from the UK and USA assessed the likelihood of such slowdowns in large model ensembles and the role that internal variability plays in recent Arctic sea-ice changes. They find that almost all models see similar pauses in individual simulations, with an approximately 20% chance in the overall model ensemble. Simulations that show similar pauses between 2005 and 2024 also show that this slowdown might persist for another 5–10 years, before a further decline is observed. These findings indicate that the recent slowdown is not exceptional and can be expected even in a warming world due to internal variability.Original reference: Geophys. Res. Lett. 52, e2025GL116175 (2025)



